TFN Exemption Code - A payee may choose to be exempt from quoting a Tax File Number at the time of Declaration, which is indicated by a TFN Exemption Code. 1= Payee applying for a TFN - if a declaration is received from a payee who does not provide a TFN but indicates on the declaration that one has been applied for, a code of 1 can be used by the payer. This code would usually be updated with the payee's TFN or else with the TFN of 000000000 where the payee fails to provide the TFN to the payer within the 28 day period allowed. These details must be sent to the ATO on the next report following the expiry of the 28 day period. The ONLY time that the TFN Exemption Code 1 would be reported to the ATO, is where the payee has not provided a TFN and the payer/payee relationship has terminated within the 28 day period. 3 = Payee under eighteen - where the payee is a child under the age of eighteen who claims the general exemption and does not earn enough for tax to be deducted, he/she may claim an exemption from quoting a TFN. If the Payees circumstances change and the payee subsequently earns a level of income that attracts tax a TFN will be required to be provided at that time. 4 = Payee is a pensioner - where the payee is also a recipient of a social security or service pension or benefit (other than New Start, sickness allowance, special benefits or partner allowance) an exemption from quoting a TFN may be claimed.

Payee Tax File Number - Tax File Number quoted by the payee or an appropriate TFN code. In circumstances where a payee is not required to quote or has chosen not to quote a TFN, one of the appropriate TFN Exemption Codes must be used in place of the TFN. 000000000 = No TFN quoted by the payee - the payee chooses not to quote a TFN or fails to provide one within the 14 day reporting period.987654321 = Alphabetic characters in quoted TFN - where a payee has quoted a TFN with non-numeric characters, the code 987654321 must be used in place of the quoted TFN. This code must also be used where the TFN quoted cannot be contained in the TFN field.

The Tax Office considers you to be an Australian resident for tax purposes if you: (1) have always lived in Australia or you have come to Australia and now live here permanently (2) are an overseas student doing a course that takes more than six months to complete (3) have been in Australia continuously for six months or more and for most of that time you worked in the one job and lived in the same place, or (4) have been in Australia for more than 183 days of the tax year (unless your usual home is overseas and you do not intend to live in Australia). If you go overseas temporarily and do not set up a permanent home in another country, you may continue to be treated as an Australian resident for tax purposes.
From 1 July 2016, any person who is temporarily in Australia for a working holiday will be treated as a non-resident for tax purposes, regardless of how long they are in Australia. For example: any person in Australia on a 417 or 462 visa. For further information on Residency for Tax Purposes see Residency Overview on the ATO Website at https://www.ato.gov.au
